Every Angular developer has stared at a sprawling NgRx codebase and thought, вҖңDo I really need an Action, Reducer, Effect, and Selector just to toggle a dropdown or manage a multi-step form?вҖқ
For years, we accepted the boilerplate because the predictable, event-driven architecture of NgRx kept our enterprise applications from collapsing into chaos. But when the Angular team introduced Signals, the community started asking a dangerous question: Should we abandon traditional NgRx entirely?
The answer is a resounding no.
The new gold standard in modern Angular architecture isnвҖҷt about choosing between global event-driven state and local reactive state. ItвҖҷs about seamlessly combining them. Here is how to build a scalable, developer-friendly architecture using traditional NgRx for global orchestration and the new NgRx SignalStore for highly reactive, local feature state.
The Core Philosophy: Two Brains are Better Than One
To understand this architecture, you have to stop looking at state as a single monolith. Your application actually has two different вҖңnervous systems,вҖқ and they need different tools.

вҖў The Global Nervous System (Traditional NgRx)
This is your appвҖҷs central hub. It is event-driven, declarative, and shared. Components here donвҖҷt mutate state; they shout into the void that something happened (e.g., вҒ [Auth] User Logged InвҒ ), and the global store decides how to react.
What lives here?
User authentication and permissions.
Application-wide settings (dark mode, language preferences).
Shared entity caches used across completely unrelated features.
Cross-cutting events (handling 401 Unauthorized API responses via Effects).
2. The Local Brain (NgRx SignalStore)
This is the state tied directly to a specific feature or route. It is method-based, imperative, and highly reactive. It lives and dies with the component or route it serves.
What lives here?
The data currently loaded in a specific data grid or dashboard.
Pagination, sorting, and filtering parameters for a single page.
Complex, multi-step form state.
Direct API orchestrations for a localized feature.
The Blueprint: Folder Structure
When you mix paradigms, your boundaries must be visually obvious the second a developer opens the repository. We lean heavily into Domain-Driven Design (DDD) to keep the global state pure and the feature states isolated.
src/app/
в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җ core/ # рҹҢҚ THE GLOBAL ZONE (Loaded on startup)
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ services/
в”Ӯ в””в”Җв”Җ state/ # Traditional NgRx
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ app.state.ts
в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ auth/
в”Ӯ в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ auth.actions.ts
в”Ӯ в”Ӯ в”ңв”Җв”Җ auth.effects.ts
в”Ӯ в”Ӯ в””в”Җв”Җ auth.reducer.ts
в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җ shared/ # рҹ§ұ REUSABLE UI (Dumb components only)
в”Ӯ в””в”Җв”Җ components/
в”Ӯ в””в”Җв”Җ ui-button/ # No state injected here!
в”Ӯ
в””в”Җв”Җ features/ # рҹ§© THE FEATURE ZONE (Lazy-loaded)
в”Ӯ
в””в”Җв”Җ profile/
в”ңв”Җв”Җ components/
в”ңв”Җв”Җ services/
в”ңв”Җв”Җ profile.routes.ts
в””в”Җв”Җ store/ # Local SignalStore
в””в”Җв”Җ profile.store.ts
The Golden Rule: Features are completely selfish. The вҒ profileвҒ  feature is never allowed to import a SignalStore from the вҒ ordersвҒ  feature. If they need to communicate, the feature must dispatch a global action.
Building the Bridge: How They Talk
The true power of this architecture is how easily these two systems interact. Because both are built for the modern Angular ecosystem, your local SignalStore can inject the global вҒ StoreвҒ  to read global context and dispatch global events.
LetвҖҷs look at a practical example. Imagine a вҒ ProfileStoreвҒ  (our local SignalStore) that needs to update a userвҖҷs avatar. It needs the вҒ userIdвҒ  from the Global Store to make the API call, and once successful, it needs to dispatch a global action so the appвҖҷs top navigation bar updates the userвҖҷs picture.
import { inject } from '@angular/core';
import { Store } from '@ngrx/store';
import { signalStore, withState, withMethods, patchState, withComputed } from '@ngrx/signals';
import { rxMethod } from '@ngrx/signals/rxjs-interop';
import { pipe, switchMap, tap } from 'rxjs';// 1. Import Global State selectors and actions
import { selectUserId } from '../../core/state/auth/auth.selectors';
import { AuthActions } from '../../core/state/auth/auth.actions';
import { ProfileApiService } from '../services/profile-api.service';
interface ProfileState {
isUploading: boolean;
uploadError: string | null;
}
const initialState: ProfileState = {
isUploading: false,
uploadError: null,
};
export const ProfileStore = signalStore(
withState(initialState),
// 2. Read from the Global Store using computed signals
withComputed((_, globalStore = inject(Store)) => ({
currentUserId: globalStore.selectSignal(selectUserId)
})),
withMethods((
store,
api = inject(ProfileApiService),
globalStore = inject(Store) // Inject the global NgRx Store
) => ({
// 3. Imperative method called directly by the UI component
updateAvatar: rxMethod<File>(
pipe(
tap(() => patchState(store, { isUploading: true, uploadError: null })),
switchMap((file) => {
// Use the computed signal derived from global state
const userId = store.currentUserId();
return api.uploadAvatar(userId, file).pipe(
tap({
next: (response) => {
patchState(store, { isUploading: false });
// 4. Dispatch to the Global Store so the rest of the app reacts!
globalStore.dispatch(AuthActions.avatarUpdated({ newUrl: response.url }));
},
error: (err) => {
patchState(store, { isUploading: false, uploadError: err.message });
}
})
);
})
)
)
}))
);
Why this is a game-changer:

вҖў Zero Global Clutter: The global store doesnвҖҷt need to know about вҒ isUploadingвҒ  or вҒ uploadErrorвҒ . That transient UI state is handled perfectly by the local SignalStore.

вҖў 2. Strict Traceability: The moment the avatar actually changes, a formal action (вҒ [Auth] Avatar UpdatedвҒ ) is dispatched globally, allowing the Redux DevTools to track the data flow across the app.

вҖў 3. Incredible DX: The component developer just calls вҒ profileStore.updateAvatar(file)вҒ . They donвҖҷt have to wire up complex effects or track loading selectors.

вҖў The Takeaway

вҖў By marrying traditional NgRx with the new SignalStore, you get the best of both worlds. You retain the strict, event-driven traceability required to keep an enterprise app stable, while recovering the rapid, imperative developer experience that makes building individual features actually fun again.

вҖў Stop fighting the boilerplate, and start putting your state where it actually belongs.
